+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01U7o7vQVw1XZeKbkhowgD2v","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The swapping of input references is causing cascading problems. The issue is that when I swap wire names in all input references, it creates a cascading effect where every subsequent bit gets confused.\n\nThe fundamental problem is this: swapping gate outputs doesn't change the circuit's wiring. Gates that reference wire `c02` as input still physically connect to the wire named `c02`. The swap only changes which gate PRODUCES the signal on that wire. So I should NOT be updating input references.\n\nLet me go back to the original approach (without updating inputs) and think more carefully. The real issue is: how do I correctly trace through the circuit when a carry wire's producing gate has been swapped?\n\nThe key realization: when I do `doSwap`, I restore the circuit to its correct state. After swapping, the circuit IS correct for everything processed so far. So I should NOT update input references — the swap already makes the circuit correct because the swapped-out values are now produced by the right gates.\n\nWait, let me re-examine the original failure case. When `c02` and `t04` are swapped:\n\nBefore fix:\n- Gate A: `a02 OR b02 -> t04` (was `-> c02`, now produces on wire `t04`)\n- Gate B: `x04 XOR y04 -> c02` (was `-> t04`, now produces on wire `c02`)\n\nAfter doSwap(c02, t04):\n- Gate A: `a02 OR b02 -> c02` (restored)\n- Gate B: `x04 XOR y04 -> t04` (restored)\n\nSo after doSwap, the circuit IS correct. The problem in the original code was that when processing bit 3, `carry` was tracking the OLD wire name. Let me trace through:\n\n1. After processing bit 2 (before any swap detection): the OR gate for bit 2 outputs `t04` (because of the swap). So carry = `t04`.\n2. Processing bit 3: look for `XOR(t03, t04)`. But the gate is `XOR(t03, c02)`. In the swapped circuit, `c02` is produced by `x04 XOR y04`,