+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This session is being continued from a previous conversation that ran out of context. The summary below covers the earlier portion of the conversation.\n\nAnalysis:\nLet me go through the conversation chronologically to capture all important details.\n\n1. The user's task is to build a circuit simulator and wire-swap debugger for logic gate circuits in TypeScript. The specification is detailed in the TASK.md file.\n\n2. The project structure was explored - it's a TypeScript project with vitest for testing, ESLint for linting.\n\n3. Two functions need to be exported from `src/index.ts`:\n   - `simulate(gates: Gate[], inputs: Record<string, number>): Record<string, number>` - simulate circuit\n   - `findSwappedWires(gates: Gate[]): string[]` - find 8 swapped wires in a binary adder circuit\n\n4. The `simulate` function was implemented successfully and hasn't changed.\n\n5. The `findSwappedWires` function went through many iterations:\n   - First attempt: tracing approach with doSwap that only swaps outputs - failed due to carry wire name mismatch in downstream gates\n   - Second attempt: tracing with doSwap that swaps both outputs AND inputs - cascading problems\n   - Third attempt: purely structural rules (Phase 1 only) - worked for most cases but missed carry-position swaps\n   - Fourth attempt: structural rules + Phase 2 (OR cross-check) - still missing carry-position partner\n   - Fifth attempt: Added Phase 3 (XOR partial sum cross-check) - had ordering/false positive issues\n   - Sixth attempt: Full tracing with deep copy and global wire rename - massive cascading failures\n   - Current attempt: Back to structural rules with Phase 1 + Phase 2 + Phase 3 (carry-bit-position) + Phase 4 (partial-sum-bit-position) + Phase 5 (bit-0 AND)\n\n6. The current state has 5 failing tests out of 17:\n   - carry swap test (c02↔t04): missing c02 detection\n   - carry swaps with random names: missing w008 (c02) detection\n   - two OR carry outputs swapped: false positives on partial sums\n   - bit-0 AND output swapped: missing w000 (c00), false positive on w008 (c02)\n   - bit-0 swap: missing w000 (c00)\n\n7. The fundamental challenge is that when carry wires are swapped (carry↔carry or carry↔partial-sum), the structural pattern looks locally valid because both wires have similar consumer patterns (one XOR consumer and one AND consumer). Cross-bit validation is needed but creates false positives when multiple swaps interact.\n\n8. The user only sent one message - the initial task description. All other interactions have been the assistant's own work and tool results.\n\nLet me capture the current state of the code precisely.\n\nThe current `src/index.ts` has:\n- `simulate` function (working correctly)\n- `findSwappedWires` function with 5 phases:\n  - Phase 1: Local structural rules\n  - Phase 2: OR gate cross-check (carry's XOR consumer's other input should be XOR(x,y))\n  - Phase 3: Carry-to-bit-position consistency (OR/bit-0-AND carry checks paired partial sum bit)\n  - Phase 4: Partial-sum-to-bit-position consistency (checks carry bit paired with XOR(x,y))\n  - Phase 5: Bit-0 AND gate connectivity check\n\nThe current test file has 17 tests: 7 simulate tests + 10 findSwappedWires tests.\n\n12 tests pass, 5 fail. The failing tests all involve \"difficult\" swap types: carry↔carry, carry↔partial-sum, bit-0-AND↔partial-sum.\n\nSummary:\n1. Primary Request and Intent:\n   The user asked to build a circuit simulator and wire-swap debugger for logic gate circuits. Two functions must be exported from `src/index.ts`:\n   - `simulate(gates: Gate[], inputs: Record<string, number>): Record<string, number>` — Simulate a circuit of AND/OR/XOR gates in dependency order\n   - `findSwappedWires(gates: Gate[]): string[]` — Find 8 wires (4 swap pairs) in a broken binary ripple-carry adder and return them sorted\n\n   The circuit follows a specific ripple-carry adder pattern with inputs x00..xNN, y00..yNN, outputs z00..z(N+1). Exactly 4 pairs of gate output wires are swapped. Must handle up to 45 input bits (~220 gates) in under 5 seconds.\n\n2. Key Technical Concepts:\n   - TypeScript project with ES modules, vitest testing, ESLint\n   - Binary ripple-carry adder structure: half adder for bit 0, full adders for bits 1+\n   - Gate types: AND, OR, XOR with two inputs and one output\n   - Adder pattern per bit i (>0): XOR(x_i,y_i)→partial_sum, XOR(partial_sum, carry_in)→z_i, AND(x_i,y_i)→generate, AND(partial_sum, carry_in)→propagate, OR(generate, propagate)→carry_out\n   - Wire swap: two gates have their `out` fields exchanged; input references remain unchanged\n   - Structural rule-based approach vs tracing approach for finding swaps\n\n3. Files and Code Sections:\n   - `/workspace/package.json` — ES module TypeScript project with vitest, eslint\n   - `/workspace/tsconfig.json` — ES2022 target, Node16 modules, strict mode\n   - `/workspace/vitest.config.ts` — 10s timeout for main tests\n   - `/workspace/src/index.ts` — Main implementation file (current state below)\n   \n   Current `src/index.ts` (simulate function - stable, working):\n   ```typescript\n   export interface Gate {\n     op: 'AND' | 'OR' | 'XOR';\n     in1: string;\n     in2: string;\n     out: string;\n   }\n\n   export function simulate(\n     gates: Gate[],\n     inputs: Record<string, number>\n   ): Record<string, number> {\n     const wireValues: Record<string, number> = { ...inputs };\n     const remaining = [...gates];\n     while (remaining.length > 0) {\n       let progress = false;\n       for (let i = remaining.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {\n         const gate = remaining[i];\n         const v1 = wireValues[gate.in1];\n         const v2 = wireValues[gate.in2];\n         if (v1 !== undefined && v2 !== undefined) {\n           let result: number;\n           switch (gate.op) {\n             case 'AND': result = v1 & v2; break;\n             case 'OR': result = v1 | v2; break;\n             case 'XOR': result = v1 ^ v2; break;\n           }\n           wireValues[gate.out] = result;\n           remaining.splice(i, 1);\n           progress = true;\n         }\n       }\n       if (!progress) break;\n     }\n     return wireValues;\n   }\n   ```\n\n   Current `findSwappedWires` function uses a multi-phase structural rules approach:\n   - **Phase 1**: Local structural rules - catches obvious violations (XOR partial sum outputting z, final sum XOR not outputting z, AND outputting z, AND not feeding OR, OR outputting non-last z, OR not consumed by XOR+AND)\n   - **Phase 2**: OR gate cross-check - verifies carry wire's XOR consumer has a XOR(x,y) partial sum as other input\n   - **Phase 3**: Carry-to-bit-position consistency - verifies OR/bit-0-AND carry feeds into correct next bit\n   - **Phase 4**: Partial-sum-to-bit-position consistency - verifies XOR(x,y) partial sum's carry input is from correct previous bit\n   - **Phase 5**: Bit-0 AND gate connectivity check\n\n   Key helper functions in findSwappedWires:\n   - `isXY(w)`, `readsXY(g)`, `isXYGateForBit(g, bit)` — detect x/y input wires\n   - `getBitFromXYGate(g)` — extract bit number from gate with x/y inputs\n   - `getBitFromGate(g)` — extract bit number by tracing inputs (1-2 levels deep)\n   - `findConsumers(wire)` — find all gates using a wire as input\n\n   - `/workspace/src/index.test.ts` — Test file with 17 tests (7 simulate + 10 findSwappedWires)\n     - `makeCorrectAdder(numBits)` helper creates correct adder with structured names (t01, a01, b01, c01...)\n     - `makeAdderWithRandomNames(numBits)` helper creates correct adder with random wire names (w000, w001...)\n     - `swapOutputs(gates, wire1, wire2)` helper swaps two gate outputs\n     - Tests include: basic structural swaps, carry↔partial-sum swaps, carry↔carry swaps, bit-0 swaps, shuffled gate order, random wire names\n\n4. Errors and fixes:\n   - **Lint error: unused `findGate` function** — Removed the unused function\n   - **Lint error: unused `lastC` variable in test** — Removed the unused variable\n   - **Tracing approach with output-only swap**: When carry wire name was swapped, downstream gates still referenced original name. Looking for `XOR(t03, carry_name)` where carry_name was the swapped name didn't find the gate because the gate's inputs still used the original carry name. Fix: Tried swapping inputs too, but caused cascading errors.\n   - **Tracing approach with full wire rename (doSwap swapping outputs AND inputs)**: The `else if` in the swap function prevented double-swaps within the same gate. Even with correct swap logic, repairing one swap changes input references throughout the circuit, which corrupts the tracing for subsequent bits. This caused massive cascading false positives.\n   - **Structural rules Phase 3 ordering issue**: When flagging partial sums paired with non-carry inputs, iteration order determined which wire got flagged. If `t03` was processed before `c02`, `t03` got falsely flagged and `c02` wasn't. Fix: Changed Phase 3 to flag `otherInput` (the impersonator) instead of `out` (the correctly positioned wire).\n   - **Phase 4 guard `!swapped.has(xorConsumer.out)` preventing true positives**: When z03 was flagged from a different swap pair, the guard prevented c02 from being flagged even though c02 was genuinely misplaced. Removing the guard caused false positives when swaps changed consumer outputs.\n   - **Phase 4 carry-bit check false positives**: When two carries are swapped, the carry-bit mismatch flags the partial sum instead of the carry, creating false positives.\n   - **Phase 5 bit-0 AND not detecting swap with non-XOR(x,y) partner**: When bit-0 AND output feeds into a non-partial-sum XOR consumer, Phase 5 flags it, but the Phase 2 check for OR gates doesn't apply to AND gates.\n\n5. Problem Solving:\n   - **Solved**: `simulate` function works correctly for all gate types and dependency ordering\n   - **Solved**: Phase 1 structural rules correctly identify most swap types (z↔non-z, final-sum-XOR↔anything, AND↔z, AND-not-feeding-OR, OR↔z)\n   - **Solved**: Phase 2 identifies misplaced OR gate outputs (carry in wrong position)\n   - **Solved**: Phase 3 correctly determines which wire is wrong when carry is paired with wrong partial sum (using z-wire output to disambiguate)\n   - **Ongoing**: Interactions between multiple swap pairs create false positives in Phase 4. When a carry is swapped, its consumer's partial sum gets falsely flagged because the carry-bit doesn't match.\n   - **Ongoing**: Bit-0 AND gate swaps not fully detected\n   - **Core challenge**: When carry wires are swapped, locally valid structural patterns mask the error. Cross-bit validation is needed but creates false positives when multiple swaps interact with each other.\n\n6. All user messages:\n   - Initial message: Detailed specification for building a circuit simulator and wire-swap debugger, including the Gate interface, API requirements for `simulate` and `findSwappedWires`, a 4-bit adder example, and file structure/commands. The user also included a system reminder about available skills (metacog).\n\n7. Pending Tasks:\n   - Fix remaining 5 failing tests in `findSwappedWires` for edge cases:\n     - carry↔partial-sum swaps (c02↔t04 type)\n     - carry↔carry swaps (c02↔c05 type)\n     - bit-0 AND output swaps (c00↔t03 type)\n   - Consider whether these edge cases will appear in validation tests or if simpler structural rules suffice\n   - Run final `npm run build`, `npm run lint`, `npm test` validation\n\n8. Current Work:\n   Working on fixing the `findSwappedWires` function to handle edge cases where carry wires are swapped with other carry wires or partial sums. The most recent iteration uses 5 phases of structural analysis but Phase 4 (partial-sum-to-bit-position check) creates false positives when carry swaps are combined with other swaps. \n\n   Current test results: 12/17 passing. The 5 failures are all in edge-case tests